{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657927"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:38:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:38:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20690"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20690"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95598"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13566"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78409"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11657"},{"type":"tags","id":"12567"},{"type":"tags","id":"12568"},{"type":"tags","id":"12569"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32546"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95598"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman who is 20 weeks pregnant attends her antenatal appointment. She reports smoking half a pack of cigarettes daily for the past 15 years. Her obstetrician discusses the risks of continued tobacco use during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiological effects of nicotine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreases cardiac contractility and output","Prevents oxygen transport across the placenta","Stimulates catecholamine release from sympathetic neurones","Directly causes DNA mutations in foetal cells","Inhibits acetylcholine receptors in the central nervous system"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENicotine, the addictive alkaloid in tobacco, \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulates catecholamine release from sympathetic neurones\u003C/strong\u003E. This mechanism explains the acute cardiovascular effects of smoking, including increased heart rate, elevated blood pressure, and enhanced cardiac contractility and output. Nicotine achieves these effects by binding to nicotinic acetylcholine receptors in the brain and peripheral nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits acetylcholine receptors in the central nervous system\u003C/strong\u003E - Nicotine actually activates (not inhibits) nicotinic acetylcholine receptors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly causes DNA mutations in foetal cells\u003C/strong\u003E - While tobacco smoke contains carcinogens that can cause DNA mutations, nicotine itself is not a direct mutagen. Nicotine does affect foetal brain development and contributes to preterm birth and stillbirth through other mechanisms.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases cardiac contractility and output\u003C/strong\u003E - Nicotine actually increases (not decreases) cardiac contractility and output through its sympathomimetic effects.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents oxygen transport across the placenta\u003C/strong\u003E - While smoking can reduce oxygen delivery to the foetus (primarily through carbon monoxide binding to haemoglobin), nicotine itself does not directly prevent oxygen transport across the placenta.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETobacco use is the leading preventable cause of death and is responsible for more than 400,000 deaths annually in the United States. It is the primary exogenous cause of human cancers, accounting for 90% of lung cancer cases. Second-hand smoke exposure is also harmful and can cause lung cancer in non-smokers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tobacco smoking is the leading preventable cause of death and is responsible for 90% of lung cancer cases.","Nicotine is an addictive alkaloid in tobacco that binds to nicotinic acetylcholine receptors and stimulates catecholamine release.","Second-hand smoke exposure can cause lung cancer in non-smokers and contributes to significant mortality.","Nicotine exposure during pregnancy affects foetal brain development and contributes to preterm birth and stillbirth."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 9; page 415-418."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78409"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20690"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78409"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-28T18:38:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-28T18:39:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13566"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95598"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11657"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Environmental and nutritional disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":8,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:24:29+10:30",